[StudyName "Carlsen loses but then wins back with an illegal move | World Blitz Championship"]
[ChapterName "Magnus Carlsen - Ernesto Inarkiev"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Dd70394c/VwNC25s3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Remote_Chess_Academy"]

1. e4 c5 2. a3 Nc6 (2... g6 3. b4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6) 3. b4 cxb4 (3... Nf6 { was
also possible }) 4. axb4 Nxb4 5. d4 d5 6. c3 Nc6 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Na3 Bf5 9. Nb5 Rc8 10. Nxa7 Nxa7 (10... Ra8 11. Nb5) 11. Rxa7 e5 (11... Rxc3?! 12. Qa4+ Bd7? 13. Ra8+) (11... Nf6 12. Nf3 g6) 12. Nf3 exd4 13. Nxd4 Bd7 14. Nb5 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 Bc6 16. Bd3 Bc5 (16... Bxg2 17. Re1+ Kd8 18. Bf5 Rb8 19. Bf4 $18) 17. Re1+ Ne7 18. Ba3 Bxa3 (18... Bxa7 19. Rxe7+ Kd8 20. Nxa7 $16) 19. Rxa3 Rd8 20. Nd4 Kd7 (20... Bxg2 21. Nf5 Rxd3+ 22. Kc2 Rd8 23. Rxe7+ Kf8 24. Rd7 Rb8 25. Nd6 $14) 21. Ra7 Rhe8 (21... Nc8!?) 22. Kc2 Kc7 23. Rb1 Rb8 24. f3 Nd5? (24... g6 $14) 25. Nxc6 Kxc6 26. Bb5+ Kb6 27. Rxb7+ { At this point, Inarkiev played the
illegal 27...Ne3+. Carlsen might have won instantly by claiming the illegal
move, but instead he instinctively moved his king out of danger with 28.Kd3.
At this point, Inarkiev stopped the clocks and claimed victory on the basis
that Carlsen made an illegal move. The initial arbiter at first awarded
Inarkiev the win, but Carlsen alerted the chief arbiter, who overruled the
first arbiter, and gave Inarkiev the option of resuming the game from the
position arising after Carlsen's 28.Kd3. Inarkiev refused to play and Carlsen
was awarded the win. Inarkiev appealed the chief arbiter's decision, but his
claim was rejected by the appeal board and Carlsen's win stood. } 1-0


