1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Ndb5 (6. a3 { trying to
avoid the main lines. white simply spends a move to prevent bishop to b4. this
approach can not be too scary for black. } 6... d5!? { a logical response to whites
slow move. } 7. exd5 exd5 8. Be2 Be7 (8... Bd6!?) 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 { black has equal chances in this complicated middlegame position. his active
pieaces compansate him for his isolated pawn. }) (6. Be3?! { this does nothing
to meet black's threat of bb4. } 6... Bb4 7. Bd3 (7. f3 d5! { white is already
facing problems. }) 7... d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 { white needs to be carful not to get a
worse position. }) (6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 { this is the second main line. white
tries to harras black's knight while grabbing space. } 7... Nd5 8. Ne4! (8. Nxd5?! cxd5 { would only strenghen black's center. }) 8... Qc7 9. f4 f5!? 10. exf6 (10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. exd6 Qb6 $15 { whites pawn on d6 doesnt disturb black too much,
and he has nice control over the central squares. }) 10... gxf6! (10... Nxf6?! 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Qh5+ Kd8 13. Be3 $36 { without the knights blacks king is
much more valunarable. }) 11. c4 (11. Bd3 Qb6 12. a3 Ba6 { trying to exchange
black's bad bishop. } 13. Qh5+ Kd8 $13 { black loses the right to castle but at
the same time his strong pawn center gives his king a shelter. }) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Qxf4! $17 { is a nice trap. }) 6... Bb4! { black must play aggresively. } 7. a3! { this is whites main attempt to fight for the advantege. } (7. Nd6+ Ke7! { a key move. } 8. Nxc8+ (8. Bf4 e5 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bd2 (10. Bg5 d5! $15 { a typical device, using the misplaced position of the white knight. }) 10... Bxc3 { white will have hard times. } (10... d5!?)) (8. Nb5 a6 9. Nd4 Nxe4 $17) 8... Rxc8 9. Bd3 Re8! 10. O-O Kf8 $13 { black is fully developed and his
chances are not worse. }) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 { black must use his lead in
development by opening up the center. } 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d4 12. Ne2 (12. Ne4 Bf5 13. Bg5 Bxe4 14. Bxe4 h6) 12... Bg4 *


